b'' b'' b' p.s. any really good books on am/fm theory along with detailed' b' electrical diagrams would help a lot.' b' i have seen a lot of theory books with no circuits and a lot of' b' circuit books with no theory, but one without the other does not help.' b'' b'mixers have a wide variety of implementations; the mini-circuits' b'part you mention is a doubly-balanced diode mixer, but active ones' b'(bjt, fet) seem more popular in consumer receivers. you might' b'call mcl; they have a nice catalog.' b'' b'the universal answer for wide-coverage, theory+practice, rf design' b'is the _arrl handbook_, published by the american radio relay' b'league, the radio amateur organization. any technical bookstore' b'can order you one. the book is superb, with lots of accessible' b'theory, construction projects, and generally interesting stuff.' b'' b'you might also check out _solid state design for the radio amateur_' b'(i think), by hayward and <someone. this has sharper design' b'and test information about subsystems like mixers.' b'' b'mit advanced television research program' 